<body>
    <div class="container">
        <header>
            <h1>⚙️ U-Boot Bootloader</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">Universal Boot Loader - The Open Source Bootloader</p>
        </header>

        <div class="content-section">
            <h2>What is U-Boot?</h2>
            <p>U-Boot (Universal Boot Loader) is an open-source bootloader widely used in embedded systems. It initializes hardware, loads the operating system kernel, and provides a command-line interface for system configuration and debugging.</p>
            <p>U-Boot supports a wide range of architectures including ARM, x86, MIPS, PowerPC, and more, making it the most popular bootloader for embedded Linux devices.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="content-section">
            <h2>Boot Process Stages</h2>
            <div class="boot-stages">
                <div class="stage">
                    <div class="stage-number">1</div>
                    <h3>ROM Code</h3>
                    <p>CPU executes built-in ROM code that loads first-stage bootloader</p>
                </div>
                <div class="stage">
                    <div class="stage-number">2</div>
                    <h3>SPL/TPL</h3>
                    <p>Secondary Program Loader initializes basic hardware (RAM, clocks)</p>
                </div>
                <div class="stage">
                    <div class="stage-number">3</div>
                    <h3>U-Boot Proper</h3>
                    <p>Full U-Boot loads, provides CLI and prepares kernel</p>
                </div>
                <div class="stage">
                    <div class="stage-number">4</div>
                    <h3>Kernel Boot</h3>
                    <p>Loads Linux kernel and device tree into memory</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="content-section">
            <h2>How U-Boot Works</h2>
            
            <div class="diagram">
                <strong>Boot Flow</strong>
                <div class="arrow">↓</div>
                <p>Power On → ROM Code → SPL → U-Boot → Kernel → OS</p>
            </div>

            <h3>Initialization Phase</h3>
            <p>When powered on, U-Boot performs several critical tasks:</p>
            <div class="feature-list">
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>Hardware Init</strong><br>
                    Sets up CPU, memory controller, clocks
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>Memory Setup</strong><br>
                    Initializes and tests RAM
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>Device Detection</strong><br>
                    Discovers storage devices, network interfaces
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>Environment Load</strong><br>
                    Loads configuration variables
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Command Line Interface</h3>
            <p>U-Boot provides a powerful CLI for system management:</p>
            <div class="code-block">
=> printenv          # Display environment variables
=> setenv bootargs console=ttyS0,115200
=> saveenv          # Save environment to storage
=> fatload mmc 0:1 0x80000000 uImage
=> bootm 0x80000000 # Boot kernel from memory address
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="content-section">
            <h2>Key Features</h2>
            <div class="feature-list">
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>Multi-Architecture</strong><br>
                    Supports ARM, x86, MIPS, RISC-V, and more
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>Network Boot</strong><br>
                    TFTP, NFS, HTTP support
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>File Systems</strong><br>
                    FAT, ext2/3/4, UBIFS, JFFS2
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>Scripting</strong><br>
                    Automated boot sequences
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>Firmware Update</strong><br>
                    Flash memory programming
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <strong>Device Tree</strong><br>
                    Hardware description support
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="content-section">
            <h2>Common Use Cases</h2>
            <h3>Embedded Linux Devices</h3>
            <p>U-Boot is the standard bootloader for:</p>
            <ul style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                <li>Single-board computers (Raspberry Pi, BeagleBone)</li>
                <li>IoT devices and sensors</li>
                <li>Network routers and switches</li>
                <li>Industrial control systems</li>
                <li>Automotive systems</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Development and Debugging</h3>
            <p>Developers use U-Boot to test kernels, debug hardware issues, and perform firmware updates without needing external programmers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="content-section">
            <h2>Environment Variables</h2>
            <p>U-Boot uses environment variables to control boot behavior:</p>
            <div class="code-block">
bootcmd=mmc dev 0; fatload mmc 0:1 0x80000000 zImage; bootz 0x80000000
bootargs=console=ttyS0,115200 root=/dev/mmcblk0p2 rootwait
bootdelay=3
            </div>
            <p>These variables determine what device to boot from, kernel parameters, and automatic boot timing.</p>
        </div>

